{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"48ce1e80-4a5d-4568-b96c-85a5e90efecb","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. These contain the stack trace, signal info, and thread state.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited   # enable before running\n   ```\n   Cores land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. macOS disables them by default, and SIP may block them entirely.\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, the `.ips` crash report is usually your best bet since `createdump` isn't bundled. It includes the faulting address and native stack frames, which you can symbolicate if you kept the `.dsym` bundle.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"46013d24-3f8e-4d3d-9183-4bd1f4918ac4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":295,"requestId":"A0D3:35214E:9547EA:B780AF:6A013671"},"id":"7b331cf2-fc3a-4166-aac7-6be789c8f019","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:52:57.659Z","parentId":"e5e3202b-bc2b-4259-9541-d6a74b33dad7"}
